male":"1394–Afdød","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"omkring 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"omkring 1410","about 1394":"omkring 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Irland"},"nl":{"about 1394–":"circa 1394–Overleden","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Overleden","1425–Female":"1425–Overleden","1394–Female":"1394–Overleden","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"circa 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"circa 1410","about 1394":"circa 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Ierland"},"en":{"about 1394–":"about 1394–Deceased","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1394–Female":"1394–Deceased","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"about 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"about 1410","about 1394":"about 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sergeant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Sargent  .","French: variant of   Sergent  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Yeoman","meanings":["English and Scottish: status name, from Middle English <i>yoman</i>, <i>yeman</i>, used of an attendant of relatively high status in a noble household, ranking between a   Sergeant   and a   Groom  , or between a   Squire   and a   Page  . The word probably originated as a shortened form of Middle English <i>yonge man</i>. Later in the Middle English period it came to be used of a modest independent freeholder, and this latter sense may well lie behind some examples of the surname. In Scotland by the 16th century it had come to denote a landholder next in rank below a gentleman, specifically one who owned land worth at least forty shillings a year."]},{"name":"Sargent","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>sergeaunt</i> ‘servant’ (Old French <i>sergent</i>, <i>serjant</i>). The surname probably originated for the most part in this sense, but the word also developed a number of more specialized meanings in the medieval period, including ‘tenant by military service below the rank of knight’. It was also used for a variety of administrative and legal offices, which may have contributed to the development of the surname. The sense ‘non-commissioned officer’ did not arise until the 16th century. Compare   Sergent  .","History: William Sargent (1624–1717) came to Gloucester, MA, from Devon, England before 1678. Many of his descendants distinguished themselves in the civil and military affairs of the colonies and some in literary or artistic paths, notably the portrait painter John Singer Sargent (1856–1925)."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Robert Sergeant Knight was born about 1394, in Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland. She had at least 2 daughters with Sir Robert Serjeant."},"et":{"about 1394–":"umbes 1394–Surnud","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1394–Female":"1394–Surnud","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"umbes 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"umbes 1410","about 1394":"umbes 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1394–":"noin 1394–Kuollut","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1394–Female":"1394–Kuollut","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"noin 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"noin 1410","about 1394":"noin 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Irlanti"},"fr":{"about 1394–":"environ 1394–Décédée","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Décédée","1425–Female":"1425–Décédée","1394–Female":"1394–Décédée","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"environ 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"environ 1410","about 1394":"environ 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Robert Sergeant Knight est née environ 1394, à Castleknock, County Dublin, Irlande. Elle a eu au moins 2 filles avec Sir Robert Serjeant."},"de":{"about 1394–":"um 1394–Verstorben","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Verstorben","1425–Female":"1425–Verstorben","1394–Female":"1394–Verstorben","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","about 1425":"um 1425","1440":"1440","1394":"1394","about 1410":"um 1410","about 1394":"um 1394","1390":"1390","Castleknock, County Dublin, Ireland":"Castleknock, County Dublin, Irland","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Robert Sergeant Knight wur